<!-- EXTENDED BIO -->
<div class="about-full">
  <div class="about-full-intro">
    <p>Jay Trainer is a songwriter from Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, whose music lives at the intersection of folk, acoustic rock, and something harder to name — the sound of a place, a season, a memory that won't quite let go.</p>
    <p>He spent twenty years on the West Coast, carrying Pittsburgh with him in the songs even when he was far from the rivers and hills. Years ago he made his way back, not as a career move or a retreat, but because Pittsburgh felt like the truth of him — the place that made the music make sense.</p>
    <p>With eight releases spanning nearly two decades, the catalogue tells a story of quiet persistence. From the San Francisco-recorded *The Waking Hours* (2006) to the expansive *A Whisper of Ruin — Deluxe Edition* (2019), each album marks a chapter in a life lived through music.</p>
    <p>The work has never chased trends. It has grown like the old trees that show up again and again in the lyrics — slowly, deliberately, shaped by the particular soil of western Pennsylvania. Songs about loss and rootedness. About what it costs to leave and what it means to stay. About the deep-seated instinct that tells you, before you can even name it, that this is what you were made to do.</p>
  </div>

